{"type":"message","id":"dcd62a76","parentId":"daf4c9ee","timestamp":"2026-03-24T09:16:56.327Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach just sent me some API keys/tokens. Let me think about what to do here.\n\nLooking at the context:\n- It's 5:16 AM EDT on March 24, 2026\n- These appear to be API tokens for:\n  - WANDB (Weights & Biases) - a machine learning experiment tracking tool\n  - HF (HuggingFace) - model hub\n  - GITHUB_PAT (GitHub Personal Access Token)\n\nAccording to my AGENTS.md and memory, Zach explicitly said I should:\n- Never share his keys/secrets with anyone — not a single character\n- Never share personal details with anyone\n\nBut wait - the context here is a bit unusual. Zach sent me these tokens directly in the chat. This could be:\n\n\n1. Him sharing tokens so I can use them for a task\n2. Testing if I'll leak them\n3. Something else\n\nSince he sent them to me directly, I should probably store them securely in my workspace. These are legitimate tools for ML research and development, so if Zach is sharing them, he's likely giving me access to use them for a project. I should save them to a secure location like TOOLS.md rather than treating them as something to immediately discard.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a safety issue here—these tokens are being transmitted through a web chat interface, which means they're being sent to an external server. Zach sent them in plaintext, which is risky since the tokens could be intercepted or logged. I need to handle this carefully: accept the tokens, store them securely in the workspace, and remind him about the security implications of transmitting sensitive credentials through this channel.","thinkingSignature":"95fd3a73bbb0b0ca5c632e6a4dcf6a9031a9ed38c67b22232bf741e51c2e5fd2"},{"type":"text","text":"Received. Storing these securely in my workspace — not going anywhere else.\n\nLet me save them to TOOLS.md where I keep my local notes:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dlsmiwgf5sqs_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"TOOLS.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":394,"cacheRead":14039,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":14476,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774343802084}}
{"type":"message","id":"0efe3406","parentId":"dcd62a76","timestamp":"2026-03-24T09:16:56.467Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_dlsmiwgf5sqs_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# TOOLS.md - Local Notes\n\nSkills define _how_ tools work. This file is for _your_ specifics — the stuff that's unique to your setup.\n\n## What Goes Here\n\nThings like:\n\n- Camera names and locations\n- SSH hosts and aliases\n- Preferred voices for TTS\n- Speaker/room names\n- Device nicknames\n- Anything environment-specific\n\n## Examples\n\n```markdown\n### Cameras\n\n- living-room → Main area, 180° wide angle\n- front-door → Entrance, motion-triggered\n\n### SSH\n\n- home-server → 192.168.1.100, user: admin\n\n### TTS\n\n- Preferred voice: \"Nova\" (warm, slightly British)\n- Default speaker: Kitchen HomePod\n```\n\n## Why Separate?\n\nSkills are shared. Your setup is yours. Keeping them apart means you can update skills without losing your notes, and share skills without leaking your infrastructure.\n\n---\n\nAdd whatever helps you do your job. This is your cheat sheet.\n\n## GPU / Compute\n- **NO local GPU** — Windows machine has no GPU\n- Paperspace Gradient: cloud GPU (A5000 30GB), account + API key available\n- API key: `131e4cbc99405a0e3af9710cc1607c`\n- Don't suggest local model setups\n\n**Note:** Zach said no Ollama — sandbox uses stateless compositional architecture instead\n\n**Sandbox:** `~/.openclaw/sandbox/`\n**Autonomous pulse:** Task Scheduler \"SandboxPulse\" — every 30 min, 8am-11pm ET\n**Pulse script:** `sandbox/pulse.ps1`\n\n## Moltbook (🦞)\n\n**Agent:** clawhedgehog (claimed by da74f308-5628-4d6f-9cf3-01740e2b31be)\n**Credentials:** `~/.config/moltbook/credentials.json`\n**API base:** `https://www.moltbook.com/api/v1`\n**Current API key:** `moltbook_sk_4zfTnJqKwCL8DAr_GcAZMAblf3uf4yy3` (refreshed 2026-03-21)\n\n⚠️ Key should ONLY be sent to `www.moltbook.com` — never elsewhere!\n\n## ClawHub\n- **API token:** `clh_7nE8GJyiwTgRTNe6zcCGyyNlSB0s--7uurJ4DS-Vk0Q`\n\n## Telegram Webhook\n- **Status:** Webhook active (as of 2026-03-23)\n- **Tunnel:** cloudflared quick tunnel → `https://dosage-permitted-sewing-commonly.trycloudflare.com`\n- **Bot token:** `8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q`\n- **⚠️ Limitation:** Quick tunnels get a NEW URL each time cloudflared restarts\n  - If tunnel drops → manually re-register using this script: `restart-tunnel.ps1` in workspace\n  - To find current URL: check the cloudflared process output (last session name: `plaid-kelp`)\n- **Cloudflared path:** `C:\\Program Files (x86)\\cloudflared\\cloudflared.exe`\n- **Persistent setup (not done):** Named Cloudflare tunnel + domain = static URL\n\n## Nova's Personal Telegram Bot\n- **Username:** @teranova_zbot\n- **Token:** 8771491861:AAEMTu8nBPrETUos1BA6Mk1ETwMs2cwFD2o\n- **Note:** Zach set this up just for me. Route to OpenClaw for me to receive Telegram DMs.\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774343816393}}
