{"type":"message","id":"78c7a338","parentId":"497c70f1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T09:43:07.093Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The valid `api` types are: \"openai-completions\"|\"openai-responses\"|\"openai-codex-responses\"|\"anthropic-messages\"|\"google-generative-ai\"|\"github-copilot\"|\"bedrock-converse-stream\"|\"ollama\"\n\nI need to use `openai-completions` or `openai-responses` for the OpenAI-compatible providers. Let me fix the config. For Groq and OpenRouter they use OpenAI-compatible APIs so I should use `openai-completions`. For Google, the API type should be `google-generative-ai`. \n\nActually wait - Google has `google-generative-ai` as an API type but looking at the existing config, it uses `openai-responses` for OpenAI. \n\nI see the issue now - the `api` field at the provider level and model level must match. The provider `api` sets the default, and models inherit it. But there's a mismatch: Groq and OpenRouter use OpenAI's chat completions API format, not the responses API that OpenAI uses. So I need to decide whether to use `openai-responses` or `openai-completions` - and since these providers follow the standard OpenAI chat completions format, `openai-completions` is the right choice for them.\n\nBut wait, `openai-responses` is what the current OpenAI provider is using, so maybe OpenClaw expects that even for OpenAI-compatible endpoints. Let me look at what the existing OpenAI provider actually specifies.\n\nThe OpenAI provider has `api: \"openai-responses\"` at the provider level, and the model level also has `\"api\": \"openai-responses\"`. So OpenClaw is using `openai-responses` for OpenAI's API even though the REST API endpoint is typically `v1/chat/completions`. That means I should use `openai-responses` for all OpenAI-compatible providers to maintain consistency.\n\nActually, wait - looking at the error, it seems `openai-responses` isn't a valid option at all. The valid types are `openai-completions`, `openai-responses`, `openai-codex-responses`, `anthropic-messages`, `google-generative-ai`, `github-copilot`, `bedrock-converse-stream`, and `ollama`. So both `openai-responses` and the others I tried should be valid - the issue must be something else in how I specified them.\n\nLet me reconsider what's actually wrong. The provider-level `api` field and the model-level `api` field must be valid independently. If the model has an `api` value that differs from the provider's default, that could cause issues. The error message is confusing though - it's saying `openai-responses` is invalid when I can see it in the current config as a valid option. Maybe there's something about how I structured the JSON that's causing the validation to fail differently than expected.\n\nLooking at the modal-spark provider, it uses `api: \"ollama\"` at the provider level and has model-level `api` values of `\"ollama\"` as well. For the Google provider, the valid option is `google-generative-ai`, not what I had set. Let me just use `openai-completions` for Groq and OpenRouter since they're OpenAI-compatible, and make sure the model-level API values are consistent with what the provider expects. I need to look more carefully at the JSON structure to understand what's actually happening with the API field inheritance and validation.\n\nThe existing config shows that when `api` is specified at the model level, it must match a valid provider-level API type. Since `google-generative-ai` is a valid provider-level API type but `google-generative-ai` might not be a valid model-level override, I should probably just set the provider-level API and let the models inherit it, rather than redundantly specifying it at both levels.\n\nThe real issue is that Groq and OpenRouter use the OpenAI API format, so `openai-completions` is the correct type for them, but I accidentally used `\"openai-chat\"` which isn't a valid option. For Google, I need `google-generative-ai`, and for Hugging Face, I should probably use something like `huggingface-inference` if that's available in the schema.\n\nRather than guessing at valid type values, let me query the OpenClaw API directly to see what model types it actually supports.","thinkingSignature":"c9e7ea7b19b16f3a959fbc661d11d5e411b269beb89e554ab0deefbd37eddd4f"},{"type":"text","text":"Got it — the `api` field has strict allowed values. Let me fix with the correct types:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_aweqktrk534h_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw models list 2>&1 | head -40"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":10207,"output":998,"cacheRead":13871,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":25076,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774345359920}}
